Next week, DCS will host parent meetings to review the reopening plan. Parents will have the opportunity to attend in person or remote. The purpose of these meetings is to address any questions and concerns regarding school reopening. Parents have the choice to attend these meetings either in-person or remotely.

The meetings are scheduled as follows:

Tuesday, August 18th at 2:00 pm (auditorium)

Wednesday, August 19th at 5:00 pm (auditorium)

Thursday, August 20th at 9:00 am (auditorium)

In order to plan for number of attendees, we ask that parents rsvp to rrhinehart@dcseagles.org to indicate their preferred meeting date and format (in-person or remote). A zoom link will be sent to those parents attending the meetings remotely.

If you are unable to attend the meetings and have questions regarding the school‚Äôs reopening, please call the principal‚Äôs office.

post_text: Gabriella is a Downsville School student who, during the COVID crisis, was feeling sad . Ella stated that she was, "Getting sad about missing school, distance learning, missing my pets, friends and teachers. My teachers talked to me a lot and helped me feel safe even though I was scared about the Corona virus and missing everything." She saw on social media about a K-9 dog that had to be put out of service and decided to help that family feel better about their loss. Ella said in a speech she prepared, "Mom always teaches us to pay it forward and I was lucky to have people care about me when I was scared so we wanted to show them that we care about them." Ella contacted people and did research on the K-9 dog and his family to create a plaque in hopes the family has happy memories about the dog they lost.

As we come to the end of our school year we have one more project we‚Äôd like to see happen between our school and community.

A ribbon project. Between our school district and communtiy the roots run deep! We have always been a very connected and supportive of one another.

Please join us as we connect/tie together to show one another our support during this time.

Show your support and tie a purple, white, or both colors together around a tree, your mailbox post, porch post, or somewhere visible.

The day we can reconnect, when this pandemic is over, will be a celebratory day we can cut those ribbons downü§çüíú.

Support Each Other. School & Community.

post_text: During this weeks Zoom the sixth graders at Downsville had a "Moving Up" day by meeting with their seventh grade teachers. Mrs. Derick and Mrs. VanValkenburg facilitated the meeting and had each teacher talk with the students about what seventh grade will be like and their expectations. Students then had a chance to ask any questions that weren't answered. The sixth grade classes says a big "Thank you" for all the teachers and staff that joined our Zoom to help this process. Afterwards, the sixth graders participated in "Where's Waldo?" by trying to find where each had hid their Waldo in their room. Some were quite tricky!

post_text: The second grade visited the Lee Richardson Zoo in Kansas yesterday through the help of the Center for Interactive Learning and Collaboration. Before attending the program called "Who's Home on the Range?" the students listened to the classic song "Home on the Range". They used information from the song to think about what animals live there (buffalo, deer, antelope) and what the area is like (open areas, sunny). However, the field trip surprised us and focused on smaller animals found in the prairie habitat! We got to meet an ornate box turtle, a bull snake and a tiger salamander.

The students were then asked to design their own face masks using whatever resources they chose. Some designed theirs on paper, others created them out of what they had at home, such as socks, bandannas, coffee filters, and hair bands, but all were very creative. One student even created a scented mask!

Youth Mover, Brandon Lee White, delivers a high-energy, entertaining, and effective anti-bullying and character education program for youth across the country. As a professional ballroom dance instructor and motivational youth speaker, Brandon incorporates "teamwork, courage, character, self-discipline, exercise, and anti-bullying" into his leadership school assemblies and workshops. Brandon's full-package motivational presentation will make your students laugh, think, and grow!

post_text:
Chalk Your Walk #Chalkyourwalk #DCSSpirit

We all need a little brightening up during this self-quarantining. Grab some sidewalk chalk and get creative!

Are you getting out and going for a walk? Take a piece of chalk with you and ‚ÄúChalk Your Walk‚Äù. Walks are a fun and healthy activity.
Aren‚Äôt going anywhere? Chalk right at your home. Just getting outside in the fresh air is great for yourself!

Write a positive message.
Draw a rainbow or uplifting picture.
Put an activity on the sidewalk square (like hopping squares or spinning spiral circles).
Have FUN!
.

*SAFETY FIRST!! Be with an adult. Stay out of the road. Respect other peoples properties.

School will be open as planned on Tuesday, March 17.

post_text:
The Downsville Lions Club is providing vision screenings to PK-4.

Vision Screening Program The Lions Clubs in New York State have launched a special program to screen children for vision problems that can lead to Amblyopia, commonly referred to as ‚Äúlazy eye.‚Äù The program focuses on screening children between the ages of 6 months and 6 years. The trained volunteers from your local Lions Club will screen the children‚Äôs eyes with either a Welch Allyn vision screener or a Plusoptix screener.

What we screen for: The Vision Screeners detect risk factors that may lead to Amblyopia including: Myopia - Nearsightedness Hyperopia - Farsightedness Anisometropia - Unequal refractive power Astigmatism - Irregular eye shape Media Opacity - cataract Strabismus - Eye misalignment The Vision Screeners are approximately 85 - 95% effective in detecting problems that may lead to amblyopia.

If you have any questions or concerns, please contact the Health Office.

post_text:
A Single Bite

Our 8th graders have been given an exciting opportunity to participate in a program called ‚ÄúA Single Bite‚Äù. The goal of this program is to give exposure and education of *real food* to the students so they can be aware of making healthier nutritional choices throughout their life. This 4 week program (1 day a week) will introduce the students to new foods, locally grown foods, healthy food choices, appropriate social dining, and introduction to area hospitality professionals. Mr. Sims Foster (seen in the photos) founded this project along with his wife. They have been offering this opportunity to 8th graders in Livingston Manor. They expanded this year and reached out to offer the opportunity to Downsville.

Today was an introductory class where they sampled 4 plates. All they had to do was ‚Äútake a bite‚Äù and articulate what they liked or didn‚Äôt like about it.

The students participated and engaged well. Talked about flavor, textures, and preferences. Next week they get to go on a trip to Northern Farmhouse Pasta.

Feel free to look at their website at asinglebite.org.

post_text: Please be on the look out for Hand Foot and Mouth. Please keep your child home and contact their doctor if they present with any of these symptoms. Symptoms of fever, poor appetite, runny nose and sore throat can appear three to five days after exposure. A blister-like rash on the hands, feet and in the mouth usually develops one to two days after the initial symptoms.

post_text:
The Downsville Lion‚Äôs club will be coming soon to provide vision screenings soon. If you have any questions or concerns, please contact the Health Office.

Vision Screening Program The Lions Clubs in New York State have launched a special program to screen children for vision problems that can lead to Amblyopia, commonly referred to as ‚Äúlazy eye.‚Äù The program focuses on screening children between the ages of 6 months and 6 years. The trained volunteers from your local Lions Club will screen the children‚Äôs eyes with either a Welch Allyn vision screener or a Plusoptix screener.

What we screen for: The Vision Screeners detect risk factors that may lead to Amblyopia including: Myopia - Nearsightedness Hyperopia - Farsightedness Anisometropia - Unequal refractive power Astigmatism - Irregular eye shape Media Opacity - cataract Strabismus - Eye misalignment The Vision Screeners are approximately 85 - 95% effective in detecting problems that may lead to amblyopia.

post_text: Sixth graders have been learning about Ancient Egypt and are finishing up their unit. As a culminating activity students created amulets, which during the mummification process would be wrapped up with a mummy, to help send them to the afterlife. Part of this project included each student having to write to Osiris, the god of the Afterlife, about why their person should be allowed to enter and it includes three important facts about Ancient Egypt. Students either created an Ankh, Eye of Horus, a Scarab or a Cartouche to help send their person on to their next journey.

post_text: Kids in third grade learned the purpose of cross pollination in science this week. The activity that helped them learn this concept involved using pipe cleaners as ‚Äúbees‚Äù and transporting ‚Äúpollen‚Äù (coffee grinds or a fine orange spice) from one students flower to another. In order for pollination to occur, they had to end up with a mixture of both plant‚Äôs pollen inside each flower. Students also learned about the inner components of the flower itself that aide in pollination such as the pollen dusters and sticky stigmas!
text: Kids in third grade learned the purpose of cross pollination in science this week. The activity that helped them learn this concept involved using pipe cleaners as ‚Äúbees‚Äù and transporting ‚Äúpollen‚Äù (coffee grinds or a fine orange spice) from one students flower to another. In order for pollination to occur, they had to end up with a mixture of both plant‚Äôs pollen inside each flower. Students also learned about the inner components of the flower itself that aide in pollination such as the pollen dusters and sticky stigmas!

Mrs. Erwin‚Äôs 5th grade class just finished reading the novel Esperanza Rising By Pam Munoz Ryan. The story follows a young girl and her family with their journey from Mexico to California in the 1930‚Äôs. Each chapter title was the name of a fruit or vegetable that was harvested on the farms the character‚Äôs worked at. Mrs. Sackett and Mrs. Erwin found the fruits and vegetables and brought them in for students to try. There were many items students had not tried before. The students really enjoyed trying new foods, even if their faces say otherwise üòä The foods they tasted were: fig, almond, avocado, potato, onion, asparagus, cantaloupe, grapes, peach. *We couldn‚Äôt find guava, papaya, or plums because they were out of season, but hopefully in the spring they can try those as well.*
Students also made a hand lotion like was used in the book to help moisturize farm workers hands when they would get rough and dried out from peeling various foods. The lotion contains avocado and glycerin.

post_text: ‚ÄúMy class took a virtual field trip to Sea Turtle, Inc. in Texas today. The students got to learn a lot about different types of turtles. They met an instructor that works at the sea turtle hospital who shared about different jobs that need to be filled at their location (veterinarians, teachers, volunteers, etc.). We got to ‚Äúmeet‚Äù several turtles that are there due to sickness or injury, some of which are almost ready to be released back into the wild! One of the turtles we met had just arrived today due to shark attack injuries; however, many of the turtles are sadly injured due to human activity (boats, pollution, etc.). It was an awesome virtual field trip and we learned a lot! üòä‚Äù- 2nd Grade Mrs. Gardner

post_text:
We have been seeing a lot of Strep Throat lately and wanted to remind everyone about signs and symptoms!

Strep throat is caused by bacteria, and is passed to one another through mouth and nose secretions. It usually starts with a very sore throat and a fever. Taking antibiotics usually works well. Without medicine, strep can go on to more serious problems, such as rheumatic fever, scarlet fever and kidneys problems. Strep may also cause a skin infection called impetigo, which looks like yellow-crusted sores around the nose and mouth.

If you are unsure, please take your child to the doctor to be tested to be safe! Treatment typically involves antibiotics and a few days out of school.

Georgia Odell, RN
School Nurse

post_text: The 5th graders are studying ecosystems and made 3 eco-columns. In the terrarium the students planted rye grass seeds, mustard seeds, and alfalfa seeds. They also added a rock and dead plant material. We will be observing the growth and be adding in crickets and isopods next week. In the aquarium, students have added duckweed, algae, and elodea plants. They also added in snails and guppies. Over the next several weeks we will monitor the abiotic and biotic factors that help sustain the life so that we can better understand how real ecosystems work. Stay tuned for our findings!
